		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span class="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=492942"><span id="Scholar">pgrieco</span></a><b><span id="Scholar"><br>Scholar</span></b><br /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><br />104 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span class="notbold">Score</span>: Decent [3.33]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=pgrieco&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%">
<p>Not quite a valid argument for being a 'better Paladin'. As a Taru PLD myself (level 72), I feel a definate advantage in situations where you're trying to outlast small damage attacks, exping, and the like. But fact of the matter is that we will quickly go from being the 'best' PLD to not, because later on, I'm more likely to die from a 1300 damage Stonega IV than an Elvaan PLD is when I'm kiting Kirin; my 500+ MP isn't gonna save me, unfortunately, if I don't get a chance to use it. Generally, later on, you'll be relying on other people to heal you more than you do in an exp PT. The extra MP is great in a bind, and great for helping to keep aggro, but unfortunately, end game, there will be more situations that arise where you won't be the better PLD.</p>
